Executive Summary

IDA Source

  • The data is sourced from the Australian Bureau of Statistics https://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/Latestproducts/1380.0.55.012Main%20Features12011 Housing Arrangements where the Australian Government aims to convey information about Housing Trends for the benefit of the general public.

  • The dataset is valid because it is correctly formatted and stored. Although it is valid, it cannot be guaranteed that it is reliable. Since reliable data is defined as a trusted basis for analysis and decision - making. The accuracy of the data cannot be completely guaranteed. Despite coming from an extremely reputable source, changes in circumstances or data post-publication may affect the accuracy of the data.

  • Possible issues may include inaccurate data due to changes in census after the data was collected. This is due to the rapid changing society and economy, as the there is a time gap between data collection and it being reported.

  • Potential stakeholders include real estate agents who wish to understand the differences between dwellings in the different states and various LGAs of Australia. Additionally, it can also be helpful for the State and Local Government as it helps them idenitfy trends in housing, allowing them to use this information to create a provide an increased number of dwellings as required.

IDA Variables

  • The dataset consists of 14 column variables, each referring to different types of housing with the first column stating the LGA(s) and last column referring to the Australian states.

  • The variables used in this report are Local Government Area, Owned - outright, Rented - Real estate agent, and State.

  • These variables are the key defining information for each row of data collected. All the variables are of type character. The Owned - outright and Rented - real estate agent variables will be converted to numeric values for future calculations.

  • The Local Government Area variable consists of area name keycodes ranging from - Cities (C), Areas (A), Rural Cities (RC), Boroughs (B), Shires (S), Towns (T), Regional Councils (R), Municipalities/Municipal Councils (M), District Councils (DC), Regional Councils (RegC), and Aboriginal Councils (AC). These keycodes help to provide specific information about the areas within each state.

  • A snapshot of the data and variables is provided below.

Question 1 - Does NSW have a higher number of properties owned(outright) as compared to Victoria?

I decided to compare the the properties owned in the top two populated states in Australia in 2011, which happen to be NSW and Victoria. (na, 2012)

Hypothesis

If 1 is the average number of properties owned in NSW while 2 is the average properties owned in Victoria, we test \(H0: 1=2\) vs \(H1:1>2\) using using = 0.05 by convention.

Assumptions to perform a 2-sample t-test (assuming equal variance)

  • Both groups are independent of each other

  • No significant outliers in either groups

  • Assume that normal distribution is followed

#Isolate data property owned data for NSW
#convert the numeric character to numeric values
nsw_owned= as.numeric(gsub(",", "", data$Owned...outright[data$State == "New South Wales"]))

#create a boxplot
boxplot(nsw_owned, vic_owned, names = c("NSW", "Victoria"))

The boxplot suggests that the median values of the two states are similar. However, Victoria has greater upper-quartile and maximum, with no outliers which heavily contrasts the numerous outliers present in the NSW dataset. This may interfere with the testing. Furthermore, the IQR of NSW is smaller than that of Victoria, indicating that the NSW data is less dispersed. As such, it is better to use a Welch Two Sample T-test.

Test-Statistics

#find the length of nsw and victoria vectors 
n1 = length(nsw_owned)
n2 = length((vic_owned))

#find average
m1 = mean(nsw_owned)
m2 = mean(vic_owned)

#find variance
var1 = sd(nsw_owned) ^2
var2= sd(vic_owned)^2

#calculate t-test stat
sdp2 = ((n1 - 1) * var1 + (n2 - 1) * var2)/(n1 + n2 - 2)
se = sqrt(sdp2 * (1/n1 + 1/n2))
test = (m1 - m2 - 0)/se
test
## [1] -3.37322

Using t.test() function

t.test(nsw_owned, vic_owned, alternative="greater")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  nsw_owned and vic_owned
## t = -3.2104, df = 138.18, p-value = 0.9992
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is greater than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -4590.966       Inf
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  5393.605  8422.316

p-value and conclusion

#calculate p-value
pval = pt(abs(test), n1+n2-2, lower.tail = T)
pval
## [1] 0.9995639

As the p-value is much greater than the significance level of 0.05, the null hypothesis can not be rejected, therefore it cannot be confirmed that NSW has a higher number of properties owned than Victoria. The larger p-value suggests that there is too much variability in the sample for the hypothesis test to detect an effect - which is possibly due to the greater number of outliers in the NSW sample data.

sum(nsw_owned) > sum(vic_owned)
## [1] TRUE

This code suggests that the NSW data for homes owned outright is greater than Victorian homes owned outright.

Additional Research

From the RBA report, Graph 14 shows that Victoria has a greater number of home ownerships than NSW. This contradicts the hypothesis made, suggesting that Victoria possible has greater number of homes owned as compared to NSW. (2015)

This is further supported by the following graph, which shows that over the years, NSW continues to have a lower number of homes owned despite the increase in population. (Hall, 2017)

Sam Murden writes in the Real Estate news article that Increasing mortgage rates, combined with strong growth in home prices, have led to renting becoming an overall more affordable option across Australia now compared to this time last year (Murden, 2022), which presents a reason as to the why there is a declining trend in the number of homes owned in NSW and Victoria over the 20 years (depicted in the graph above).

Therefore, these sources act to provide information that denies the hypothesis made in Q1 - which is that NSW has a greater number of homes owned outright than Victoria.

The limitation of the additional research is that due to the rapidly changing society and economy, it is more difficult to find data and sources that provide information about housing trends from 2010.

Question 2 - Does NSW have a higher number of properties rented (by real estate owner) than Victoria?

Continuing my comparison between NSW and Victoria, I decided to compare rental properties in the two states.

Hypothesis

If 1 is the average homes rented in NSW while 2 is the average homes rented in Victoria, we test \(H0: 1=2\) vs \(H1:1>2\) using using = 0.05 by convention.

Assumptions to perform a 2-sample t-test (assuming equal variance)

  • Both groups are independent of each other

  • No significant outliers in either groups

  • Assume that normal distribution is followed

#Isolate data property owned data for NSW
#convert the numeric character to numeric values
nsw_rent= as.numeric(gsub(",", "", data$Rented...Real.estate.agent[data$State == "New South Wales"]))
vic_rent= as.numeric(gsub(",", "", data$Rented...Real.estate.agent[data$State == "Victoria"]))

Additional Research

There is a trend with milennials renting more than buying, which is comes from the shift in lifestyles and more people being able to afford to rent than to buy homes. As Marisa states young people today renting more than ever before (Sanfilippo, 2022).

From the graph in the RBA report, we can visually notice the difference between the proportion of rental dwellings between the two states, with NSW having a higher proportion. (Evans et al., 2020)

Although this data is limited to the 2016 housing trends, we can infer that 2010 projected a similar trend where NSW had higher rental dwellings than Victoria. This is due to the consistent higher population of NSW (as shown in the graph below), meaning that an increased number of people were residing in NSW, causing an increase in dwellings. Of these dwellings, as previously stated by Marisa, we can assume that there are more people renting houses rather than buying them.

Hence, we can conclude that NSW does have a greater number of homes rented as compared to Victoria in 2011.
